								<p class="text-white/90 leading-relaxed whitespace-pre-line">
Ten years,
and still my bones hum with questions.
A decade of walking,
not just paths of cities, but of selves.
I gathered fragments,
each step a shard of imagining
another world - possible, tentative,
growing in the cracks of this one.
Something took root in me.
A quiet seed that refused to stay quiet.
It stretches, still, with every friend,
every comrade,
every moment of thinking-together
under a sky I didn’t know
would feel so much like home.
Medellín.
You grew inside me
like a second heartbeat.
Streets and stories stitched into my skin,
your hills, your colours,
your collective wounds and songs.
I arrived an outsider,
a white woman alone
stammering Spanish,
yet called "Antioqueña"
with a laugh,
as if the city knew
before I did
that I belonged.
I ask:
What is "living good"?
How do we gather our bruises,
our haunted inheritances,
and turn them into
collective healing,
shared hope?
And feminisms that shape us.
How do we co-labour - not just work,
but toil, imagine,
experiment, together?
How do I create
an ethnographic experiment
that follows commoning practices,
an inquiry made with many hands,
with care, with conflict,
with reciprocity?
What is an ethnography
that shifts like river currents,
an inquiry that doesn’t seek
answers
but practices
of being-with?
And within me,
this rhizomic selfhood,
Braidotti’s ever-becoming,
a self without centre,
crisscrossed with others,
roots sprawling underground,
unseen but alive,
nourished by every encounter,
every story,
every "nos vemos"
that promises:
we will meet again,
we are not done.
I am not whole without these questions,
without these alliances,
without these kinships born in spaces
I was told weren’t mine,
but are.
And still I wonder:
How will I speak
with Silvia Rivera Cusicanqui?
What can I offer
with my fractured tongue,
my borrowed languages?
How do I weave my broken Spanish,
my European skin,
my Medellín-grown heart
into a conversation
worthy of her listening?
I don’t know yet.
But I keep making,
I keep shifting,
I keep becoming—
with them.
With you.
Nos vemos
(Photo by Sophia Manoli)
