								<p class="text-white/90 leading-relaxed whitespace-pre-line">
Amphibia City* I came to Medellín following water. Not just its path through the city, but its memory, its murmur, its pulse, its silences. The river descends from Santa Elena, a thread pulled down the mountain’s side, weaving its way through the city's fabric. Sometimes visible - gleaming, defiant - and sometimes buried, hidden beneath roads and housing blocks, as if silence could tame it.

But rivers remember. They remember being covered, channeled, disciplined in concrete. They remember what came with modernisation; the cost of progress paid in visibility. People remember too. I sat with stories of washing clothes by the river’s edge, of children swimming in its cool current, of casting lines for fish. It was a river of use, of play, of rhythm, a river that belonged to the people. One afternoon, someone leaned in quietly and said: “you know, before it was called Río Medellín or Río Porce, its name was Ana”. That was what the Indigenous people called her. Ana, a name that held intimacy, a name almost forgotten, except in passing breath. Not written on signs, but kept alive through voice. A soft resistance.

Now, the river carries other things. Chemical waste from mines upstream. Industrial runoff. And in darker times, the bodies. Wrapped, discarded. It became a route of disposal, a silent witness to what could not be spoken. I found myself learning the codes of a city that speaks in layers. The casitas de pique, once kitchens where women prepared spicy piques, flavours rooted in memory, became, too, sites of recording torture. Pique as recipe, pique as rupture. Violence folded into domestic knowledge. Even the animals spoke in code. Roosters wandering the riverbanks, unremarkable elsewhere, marked something here, narco houses, places where the rules shifted. A kind of semiotic camouflage only the city could read.

And yet the river speaks louder still. On certain afternoons, I stood at its edge and listened as the current mingled with the pulse of porro and cumbia tunes leaking from a bar door left open. It wasn’t just sound, it was a sensory archive, where grief danced with survival. Behind the Casa de la Memoria, a sleek building of testimony and trauma, the river flows on. Unauthorised, unresolved. It offers its own history, not indexed or curated, but alive. Its ecosystem stretches and contracts in conversation with the city’s wounds.

Medellín, I have come to know, is an amphibian city. It breathes through water and land, violence and resilience. It exists in dualities, holding them all in tension. Colombia too is amphibian. The memory of water runs deep among Indigenous peoples along the coasts, in the dense jungles, where rivers were lifelines long before maps drew names over them. From the port of Cartagena, enslaved people carried oceanic memory inland, tracing new lives along new rivers. Music, dance, movement born from rupture, but also from rhythm, from the sound of flowing water remembered in the body.

And then, in San Pedro Cemetery, open bottles of water placed beside graves. Offerings for the dead, so they won’t thirst in the afterlife. But the water always evaporates, rises, disappears, only to return again. An act of care that cycles, ephemeral and enduring.

In this city, I walk as a guest, but sometimes I feel more at home here than in the places that raised me. But I carry that with care. I ask: How do I listen without extracting? How do I hold stories that are not mine without possessing them? How do I make sense without making claims? The river offers no answers. Only a current to enter, to be moved by.

This, perhaps, is what I’ve learned: that memory, like water, resists being held. That healing is not arrival, but motion. And that to continue living together, we must keep listening to what flows beneath and between us. (by Penny Travlou)
